column18:
You are being asked to volunteer in a research
study. The purpose of the study is to better understand what everyday think about political figures and policies in the U.S.   If you agree to participate, your
part will be to read a set of instructions and answer some short questions. It
should take around 5 minutes of your time. Your answers are anonymous and handled with
full confidentiality.     There are no foreseeable risks or
costs to you for participating in this study. Your participation is completely
voluntary. You do not have to participate if you do not want to.   If you have any questions, concerns, or complaints about the
study, you may contact Gabriel Borelli at gborelli@princeton.edu.  You can also contact the Princeton University Institutional Review
Board at irb@princeton.edu.  If you answer "I would like
to participate" below, it means that you have read the information
contained in this form and would like to be a volunteer in this research
study.
column19:
We would like to
get your feelings toward former Vice President Joe Biden using something we call the feeling
thermometer. Ratings between 50 degrees and 100 degrees mean that you feel
favorable and warm toward Biden Ratings between 0 degrees and 50
degrees mean that you don't feel favorable toward Biden and that you
don't care too much for him. You would rate Biden at the 50
degree mark if you don't feel particularly warm or cold toward him. - Vice President Joe Biden

column29: I would prefer my son or daughter NOT be gay, lesbian, or bisexual because they would face unfair discrimination.
column30: Gays, lesbians, and bisexuals make far too much noise about their sexuality.
column31: Gays, lesbians, and bisexuals should stop shoving their lifestyle down everyone's throat.
column32:
Discrimination
		against gays, lesbians, and bisexuals is virtually nonexistent in today's
		society.
column33: Most people do NOT treat gays, lesbians, and bisexuals as fairly as they treat everyone else.
column34:
Discrimination
against women is no longer a problem in the United States.
column35:
On
		average, women have lower incomes than men.
column36:
Society
has reached the point where women and men have equal opportunities
for achievement.
column37:
Over
the past few years, the government and news media have been showing
more concern about the treatment of women than is warranted by
women's actual experiences.
column38:
It
		is easy to understand why women's groups are still concerned about
		societal limitations of women's opportunities.
column39:
The Irish,
	Italian, and many other minorities overcame prejudice and
	worked their way up.  Black people should do the same without any
	special favors.
column40: Generations of slavery and discrimination have created conditions that make it difficult for Black people to work their way out of the lower class.
column41: Over the past few years, Black people have gotten less than they deserve.
column42: It’s really a matter of some people not trying hard enough; if Black people would only try harder they could be just as well off as white people.
